Figure 1a shows the powder XRD (X-ray diffraction) patterns of pyramid shaped Cr–ZnO nanoparticles. The five strong diffraction peaks are noticed at 31.53°, 34.26°, 36.03°, 47.41°and 56.40° which can be assigned to diffraction from (100), (002), (101), (102) and (110) planes respectively, according to JCPDS card No. 36–1451. This reveals that the prepared nanoparticles were Cr–ZnO with a hexagonal wurtzite structure [10]. Similarly, Fig. 1b shows the powder XRD pattern of prepared Ni–CdO nanoparticles. The Figure specifies phase purity and morphological parameters of synthesized Ni–CdO nanoparticles. The six major diffraction peaks were observed in the XRD pattern of Ni–CdO nanoparticles at various diffraction angles, corresponding to (111), (200), (220), (311), (222) and (400) directions. All the peaks of XRD graph indexed the face centred cubic structure of Ni–CdO nanoparticles, which is in good agreement with the JCPDS card no. 78–0653 with lattice constants; a = b = c = 4.7063 Å [12]. The peaks appearing in X-ray diffraction pattern of Cr–ZnO and Ni–CdO are well matched with X-ray diffraction pattern of undoped ZnO and CdO nanoparticles (supplementary data Fig. 1S) and no additional peaks corresponding to secondary phases were emerged in the 4 wt% of Zn2+ and Ni2+ doping. The result shows that the obtained Cr–ZnO and Ni–CdO nanomaterials have good crystalline phase and high purity. The crystallite size of synthesized nanoparticles has been calculated from Debye–Scherrer equation:1Crystallite sizeD=0.9λβcosθ\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
