Optical reflectance of synthesized nanoparticles (a), Kubelka–Munk plot of Cr–ZnO (b) and Ni–CdO (c) nanoparticles
where R is the diffused reflectance of the sample and F[R] is the Kubelka–Munk function [21]. The optical band gap of Cr–ZnO and Ni–CdO nanoparticles was calculated by plotting the graph of [F(R)hν]2 against photon energy in eV. The linear part of the curve was extrapolated to (hν)2 = 0 (X-axis). Figure 5b and c shows the plot of photon energy in eV versus [F(R)hν]2 for synthesized nanoparticles. It shows the energy gap for all the synthesized samples as a function of Cr and Ni doping concentration [22]. The optical band gap was found to be 3.07 eV for Cr–ZnO and 1.94 eV for Ni–CdO nanoparticles [23].

The electrochemical properties measured from cyclic voltammetry is used identify the molecular orbital energy levels dye molecules. The molecular orbital levels of organic dye molecules have two energy levels i.e., HOMO and LUMO. The highest occupied molecular orbital (HOMO) is an outer energy level that acts as electron donor and lowest unoccupied molecular orbital (LUMO) is the deepest energy level that acts as electros acceptor (from HOMO level). When selecting the organic dyes used for DSSCs, this is very important to know the band gap, HOMO and LUMO values of dyes [24]. Figure 6 shows the cyclic voltammograms of 0.1 mM solutions of commercial Trypan Blue (TB), SPADNS (SPD) and Evans blue (EB) dyes in 0.1 M of KCl solution in the potential range from 0.2 to − 1.6 eV versus SCE (standard calomel electrode). The electrochemical glass cell consists of standard calomel electrode as a reference electrode, platinum wire as an auxiliary electrode and pencil graphite electrode as a working electrode. The potential were reference to ferrocene/ ferocenium (Fc/Fc+) as internal reference [25]. A 100 mV/s scan rate was employed for the present cyclic voltammetric studies. The cyclic voltammograms of dyes exhibit a single well shaped reduction peak in the negative potential region and no oxidation peak was seen in the reverse scan. This clearly indicates that the dyes show the irreversible redox process. Moreover, the reduction peaks obtained from the cyclic voltammetry are helps to calculating the LUMO energy levels of selected metal free organic dye molecules (TB, SPD and EB). The LUMO and HOMO levels of dyes have been calculated using the following equations (Table 2):3ELUMO/EHOMO=-(4.8+Eonsetred/Eonsetoxd)\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
